{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"620e2b7c-15cf-4e8c-9c03-892cc93fddce","content":"This repository doesn't contain MAUI-specific documentation, but I can answer based on .NET MAUI knowledge:\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This is **outdated**. It was a Xamarin.Forms API (`Xamarin.Forms.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`). In .NET MAUI, safe area padding is handled automatically by default on iOS — pages already respect the safe area insets without needing this property.\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This **does not exist** as a built-in property in .NET MAUI. It's not a valid attribute on Grid or any layout.\n\n### Correct approach for .NET 10 MAUI:\n\n1. **Safe area is respected by default** — no extra attribute needed on `ContentPage`.\n\n2. **To extend a background image behind the notch/status bar**, use padding manipulation:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\" ...>\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background image fills full screen -->\n        <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        \n        <!-- Content respects safe area via page's default padding -->\n        <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='0,47,0,34'}\">\n            <!-- your content -->\n        </VerticalStackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr programmatically remove safe area padding on the page and manage it yourself per-element.\n\nThe tutorial you found likely targets Xamarin.Forms or an older MAUI preview. For .NET 10, rely on the default safe area behavior and standard layout techniques.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b2ce73ce-ed7e-4b76-b386-a1fea1dc5aef","outputTokens":404,"requestId":"501F:4B044:1BE41C3:1F1342B:69FA9374"},"id":"bd41b291-b070-4a42-a15b-db1adde5055d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:03:57.696Z","parentId":"3816fdbb-a600-414d-8383-75e58e99017a"}
